# UI architecture (bulletproof-react)

Follow the layout documented in `ui/README.md`.

## Layers (dependency direction)

```
config, components, hooks, lib, types, utils  →  may be used by features and app
features/*                                     →  may use shared layers + same feature only; must NOT import from app/
app/*                                        →  may import features + shared layers
```

## Do

- Add new screens under `ui/src/features/<feature>/` with `components/`, `hooks/`, etc. as needed.
- Wire routes, nav, and multi-feature layout in `ui/src/app/` (e.g. `authenticated-app.tsx`).
- Put **cross-cutting UI** (used by multiple features) under `ui/src/components/` (e.g. activity overlay).
- Put **routing constants and nav** in `ui/src/config/`.
- Use **`@/`** imports for everything under `ui/src/` (see `ui/tsconfig.json`).
- Prefer **`@/components/ui/*`** for buttons, modals, alerts, nav items, cards, and dropdown menus instead of raw `className="btn …"` / duplicated modal markup. New global patterns belong in `components/ui/` with styles in `styles/components.css`.

## Don’t

- Import from `ui/src/app/` inside `ui/src/features/` (compose the other way).
- Import one feature from another; lift shared bits to `components/`, `hooks/`, or `lib/`, or pass props from `app/`.
- Add barrel `index.ts` files that re-export whole features (hurts tree-shaking in Vite).

## ESLint

Root `eslint.config.js` enforces some of this via `import/no-restricted-paths` for `ui/src`. If a rule blocks a rare legitimate case, fix the dependency direction first; only then consider a narrow exception in ESLint.
